</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q059" target="st.ii-ii.q059.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q059.contains.st.ii-ii.q059.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q059.contains.st.ii-ii.q059.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q059</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.59 — Injustice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q059.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.59 a.3 — Can one suffer injustice willingly?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q059.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one can suffer injustice willingly. For injustice is inequality, as stated above ( Article 2 ). Now a man by injuring himself, departs from equality, even as by injuring another. Therefore a man can do</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q059" target="st.ii-ii.q059.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q059.contains.st.ii-ii.q059.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q059.contains.st.ii-ii.q059.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q059</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.59 — Injustice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q059.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.59 a.4 — Is injustice a mortal sin according to its genus?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q059.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that not everyone who does an injustice sins mortally. For venial sin is opposed to mortal sin . Now it is sometimes a venial sin to do an injury: for the Philosopher says (Ethic. v, 8) in reference to thos</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060" target="concept.judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.treated_in.concept.judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.treated_in.concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 — Judgment</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-treated-in-concept-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Judgment properly denotes the act of a judge as such. Now a judge [judex] is so called because he asserts the right [jus dicens] and right is the object of justice , as</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060" target="st.ii-ii.q060.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 — Judgment</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q060.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.60 a.1 — Is judgment an act of justice?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that judgment is not an act of justice . The Philosopher says (Ethic. i, 3) that "everyone judges well of what he knows ," so that judgment would seem to belong to the cognitive faculty. Now the cognitive f</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060" target="st.ii-ii.q060.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 — Judgment</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q060.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.60 a.2 — Is it lawful to judge?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem unlawful to judge. For nothing is punished except what is unlawful. Now those who judge are threatened with punishment, which those who judge not will escape, according to Matthew 7:1 , "Judge not, and ye s</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060" target="st.ii-ii.q060.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 — Judgment</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q060.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.60 a.3 — Should judgment be based on suspicions?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not unlawful to form a judgment from suspicions. For suspicion is seemingly an uncertain opinion about an evil , wherefore the Philosopher states (Ethic. vi, 3) that suspicion is about both the t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060" target="st.ii-ii.q060.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 — Judgment</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q060.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.60 a.4 — Should doubts be interpreted favorably?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that doubts should not be interpreted for the best. Because we should judge from what happens for the most part. But it happens for the most part that evil is done, since "the number of fools is infinite " </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060" target="st.ii-ii.q060.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 — Judgment</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q060.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.60 a.5 — Should judgment always be given according to the written law?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that we ought not always to judge according to the written law . For we ought always to avoid judging unjustly . But written laws sometimes contain injustice , according to Isaiah 10:1 , "Woe to them that m</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060" target="st.ii-ii.q060.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q060.contains.st.ii-ii.q060.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 — Judgment</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q060.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.60 a.6 — Is judgment perverted by being usurped?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that judgment is not rendered perverse by being usurped. For justice is rectitude in matters of action. Now truth is not impaired, no matter who tells it, but it may suffer from the person who ought to acce</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061" target="concept.distributive_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q061.treated_in.concept.distributive_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q061.treated_in.concept.distributive_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 — The parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.distributive_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Distributive Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q061-treated-in-concept-distributive-justice-st-ii-ii-q061-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">responds the order of that which belongs to the community in relation to each single person . This order is directed by distributive justice , which distributes common goods proportionately. Hence there are two species of justice , distributive and commutative.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061" target="st.ii-ii.q061.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q061.contains.st.ii-ii.q061.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q061.contains.st.ii-ii.q061.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 — The parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q061.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.61 a.1 — Are there two species of justice, viz. distributive and commutative?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the two species of justice are unsuitably assigned, viz. distributive and commutative. That which is hurtful to the many cannot be a species of justice , since justice is directed to the common good . </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061" target="st.ii-ii.q061.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q061.contains.st.ii-ii.q061.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q061.contains.st.ii-ii.q061.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 — The parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q061.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.61 a.2 — In either case, is the mean taken in the same way?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the mean in distributive justice is to be observed in the same way as in commutative justice . For each of these is a kind of particular justice , as stated above ( Article 1 ). Now the mean is taken i</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061" target="st.ii-ii.q061.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q061.contains.st.ii-ii.q061.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q061.contains.st.ii-ii.q061.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 — The parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q061.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.61 a.3 — Is their matter uniform or manifold?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that there is not a different matter for both kinds of justice . Diversity of matter causes diversity of virtue , as in the case of fortitude and temperance . Therefore, if distributive and commutative just</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061" target="st.ii-ii.q061.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q061.contains.st.ii-ii.q061.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q061.contains.st.ii-ii.q061.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 — The parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q061.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.61 a.4 — In any of these species, is the just the same as counter-passion?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the just is absolutely the same as retaliation. For the judgment of God is absolutely just. Now the judgment of God is such that a man has to suffer in proportion with his deeds , according to Matthew </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 — Restitution</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">To restore is seemingly the same as to reinstate a person in the possession or dominion of his thing, so that in restitution we consider the equality of justice attending the payment of one thing for another, and this belongs to commutative justice . Hence restitution is an act of co</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="st.ii-ii.q062.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 — Restitution</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q062.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.62 a.1 — Of what is it an act?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that restitution is not an act of commutative justice . For justice regards the notion of what is due. Now one may restore, even as one may give, that which is not due. Therefore restitution is not the act </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="st.ii-ii.q062.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 — Restitution</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q062.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.62 a.2 — Is it always of necessity for salvation to restore what one has taken away?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not necessary to restore what has been taken away. For that which is impossible is not necessary for salvation . But sometimes it is impossible to restore what has been taken, as when a man has t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="st.ii-ii.q062.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 — Restitution</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q062.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.62 a.3 — Is it necessary to restore more than has been taken away?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not sufficient to restore the exact amount taken. For it is written ( Exodus 22:1 ): "If a man shall steal an ox or a sheep and kill or sell it, he shall restore five oxen for one ox, and four sh</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="st.ii-ii.q062.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 — Restitution</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q062.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.62 a.4 — Is it necessary to restore what one has not taken away?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a man is bound to restore what he has not taken. For he that has inflicted a loss on a man is bound to remove that loss. Now it happens sometimes that the loss sustained is greater than the thing taken</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="st.ii-ii.q062.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 — Restitution</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q062.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.62 a.5 — Is it necessary to make restitution to the person from whom something has been taken?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that restitution need not always be made to the person from whom a thing has been taken. For it is not lawful to injure anyone. Now it would sometimes be injurious to the man himself, or to others, were one</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="st.ii-ii.q062.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 — Restitution</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q062.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.62 a.6 — Is the person who has taken something away bound to restore it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that he who has taken a thing is not always bound to restore it. Restitution re-establishes the equality of justice , by taking away from him that has more and giving to him that has less. Now it happens so</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="st.ii-ii.q062.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 — Restitution</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q062.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.62 a.7 — Is any other person bound to restitution?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that restitution is not binding on those who have not taken. For restitution is a punishment of the taker. Now none should be punished except the one who sinned . Therefore none are bound to restitution sav</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062" target="st.ii-ii.q062.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q062.contains.st.ii-ii.q062.a008">
