  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.1 — Is it natural to man to possess external things?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not natural for man to possess external things. For no man should ascribe to himself that which is God's . Now the dominion over all creatures is proper to God , according to Psalm 23:1 , "The ea</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066" target="st.ii-ii.q066.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.2 — Is it lawful for a man to possess something as his own?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem unlawful for a man to possess a thing as his own. For whatever is contrary to the natural law is unlawful. Now according to the natural law all things are common property: and the possession of property is </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066" target="st.ii-ii.q066.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.3 — Is theft the secret taking of another's property?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not essential to theft to take another's thing secretly. For that which diminishes a sin , does not, apparently, belong to the essence of a sin . Now to sin secretly tends to diminish a sin , jus</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066" target="st.ii-ii.q066.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.4 — Is robbery a species of sin distinct from theft?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that theft and robbery are not sins of different species . For theft and robbery differ as "secret" and "manifest": because theft is taking something secretly, while robbery is to take something violently a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066" target="st.ii-ii.q066.a005" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a005">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a005</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a005</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.5 — Is every theft a sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a005.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that theft is not always a sin . For no sin is commanded by God , since it is written ( Sirach 15:21 ): "He hath commanded no man to do wickedly." Yet we find that God commanded theft , for it is written ( </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066" target="st.ii-ii.q066.a006" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a006">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a006</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a006</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.6 — Is theft a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a006.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that theft is not a mortal sin . For it is written ( Proverbs 6:30 ): "The fault is not so great when a man hath stolen." But every mortal sin is a great fault. Therefore theft is not a mortal sin .</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066" target="st.ii-ii.q066.a007" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a007">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a007</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a007</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.7 — Is it lawful to thieve in a case of necessity?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a007.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem unlawful to steal through stress of need. For penance is not imposed except on one who has sinned . Now it is stated (Extra, De furtis, Cap. Si quis): "If anyone, through stress of hunger or nakedness, stea</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066" target="st.ii-ii.q066.a008" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a008">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a008</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a008</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.8 — Is every robbery a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a008.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that robbery may be committed without sin . For spoils are taken by violence , and this seems to belong to the essence of robbery, according to what has been said ( Article 4 ). Now it is lawful to take spo</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066" target="st.ii-ii.q066.a009" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a009">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q066.contains.st.ii-ii.q066.a009</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 — Theft and robbery</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q066.a009</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.66 a.9 — Is robbery a more grievous sin than theft?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a009.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that theft is a more grievous sin than robbery. For theft adds fraud and guile to the taking of another's property: and these things are not found in robbery. Now fraud and guile are sinful in themselves, a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067" target="concept.judicial_process" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q067.treated_in.concept.judicial_process">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q067.treated_in.concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 — The injustice of a judge, in judging</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d12">Judicial Process</data>
  <data key="d13">process</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q067-treated-in-concept-judicial-process-st-ii-ii-q067-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">A judge's sentence is like a particular law regarding some particular fact. Wherefore just as a general law should have coercive power, as the Philosopher states (Ethic. x, 9), so too the sentence of a judge should have coercive power, whereby either party is</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067" target="st.ii-ii.q067.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q067.contains.st.ii-ii.q067.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q067.contains.st.ii-ii.q067.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 — The injustice of a judge, in judging</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q067.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.67 a.1 — Can a man justly judge one who is not his subject?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a man can justly judge one who is not subject to his jurisdiction . For it is stated ( Daniel 13 ) that Daniel sentenced the ancients who were convicted of bearing false witness. But these ancients wer</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067" target="st.ii-ii.q067.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q067.contains.st.ii-ii.q067.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q067.contains.st.ii-ii.q067.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 — The injustice of a judge, in judging</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q067.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.67 a.2 — Is it lawful for a judge, on account of the evidence, to deliver judgment in opposition to the truth which is known to him?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem unlawful for a judge to pronounce judgment against the truth that he knows , on account of evidence to the contrary. For it is written ( Deuteronomy 17:9 ): "Thou shalt come to the priests of the Levitical </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067" target="st.ii-ii.q067.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q067.contains.st.ii-ii.q067.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q067.contains.st.ii-ii.q067.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 — The injustice of a judge, in judging</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q067.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.67 a.3 — Can a judge justly sentence a man who is not accused?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a judge may pass sentence on a man who is not accused. For human justice is derived from Divine justice . Now God judges the sinner even though there be no accuser. Therefore it seems that a man may pa</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067" target="st.ii-ii.q067.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q067.contains.st.ii-ii.q067.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q067.contains.st.ii-ii.q067.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 — The injustice of a judge, in judging</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q067.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.67 a.4 — Can he justly remit the punishment?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the judge can lawfully remit the punishment. For it is written ( James 2:13 ): "Judgment without mercy" shall be done "to him that hath not done mercy." Now no man is punished for not doing what he can</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q068" target="concept.accuser_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q068.treated_in.concept.accuser_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q068.treated_in.concept.accuser_role</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q068</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.68 — Matters concerning unjust accusation</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.accuser_role</data>
  <data key="d12">Accuser</data>
  <data key="d13">role</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q068-treated-in-concept-accuser-role-st-ii-ii-q068-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q068.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">the injury of the commonwealth, a man is bound to accusation, provided he can offer sufficient proof , since it is the accuser's duty to prove : as, for example, when anyone's sin conduces to the bodily or spiritual corruption of the community. If, however, the sin be not such as to af</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q068" target="st.ii-ii.q068.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q068.contains.st.ii-ii.q068.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q068.contains.st.ii-ii.q068.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q068</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.68 — Matters concerning unjust accusation</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q068.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.68 a.1 — Is a man bound to accuse?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q068.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a man is not bound to accuse. For no man is excused on account of sin from fulfilling a Divine precept, since he would thus profit by his sin . Yet on account of sin some are disqualified from accusing</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q068" target="st.ii-ii.q068.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q068.contains.st.ii-ii.q068.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q068.contains.st.ii-ii.q068.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q068</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.68 — Matters concerning unjust accusation</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q068.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.68 a.2 — Should the accusation be made in writing?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q068.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem unnecessary for the accusation to be made in writing. For writing was devised as an aid to the human memory of the past. But an accusation is made in the present. Therefore the accusation needs not to be ma</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q068" target="st.ii-ii.q068.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q068.contains.st.ii-ii.q068.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q068.contains.st.ii-ii.q068.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q068</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.68 — Matters concerning unjust accusation</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q068.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.68 a.3 — How is an accusation vitiated?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q068.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that an accusation is not rendered unjust by calumny , collusion or evasion. For according to Decret. II, qu. iii [Append. Grat. ad can. Si quem poenituerit.], " calumny consists in falsely charging a perso</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q068" target="st.ii-ii.q068.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q068.contains.st.ii-ii.q068.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q068.contains.st.ii-ii.q068.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q068</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.68 — Matters concerning unjust accusation</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q068.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.68 a.4 — How should those be punished who have accused a man wrongfully?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q068.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the accuser who fails to prove his indictment is not bound to the punishment of retaliation. For sometimes a man is led by a just error to make an accusation, in which case the judge acquit the accuser</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q069" target="concept.defendant_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q069.treated_in.concept.defendant_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q069.treated_in.concept.defendant_role</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q069</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.69 — Sins committed against justice: of the part of the defendant</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.defendant_role</data>
  <data key="d12">Defendant</data>
  <data key="d13">role</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q069-treated-in-concept-defendant-role-st-ii-ii-q069-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q069.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Whoever acts against the due order of justice , sins mortally, as stated above ( II-II:59:4 ). Now it belongs to the order of justice that a man should obey his superior in those matters to which the rights of his authority extend. Again, the judge, as stated</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q069" target="st.ii-ii.q069.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q069.contains.st.ii-ii.q069.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q069.contains.st.ii-ii.q069.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q069</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.69 — Sins committed against justice: of the part of the defendant</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q069.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.69 a.1 — Is it a mortal sin to deny the truth which would lead to one's condemnation?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q069.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem one can, without a mortal sin , deny the truth which would lead to one's condemnation. For Chrysostom says (Hom. xxxi super Ep. ad Heb.): "I do not say that you should lay bare your guilt publicly, nor accu</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q069" target="st.ii-ii.q069.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q069.contains.st.ii-ii.q069.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q069.contains.st.ii-ii.q069.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q069</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.69 — Sins committed against justice: of the part of the defendant</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q069.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.69 a.2 — Is it lawful to defend oneself with calumnies?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q069.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem lawful for the accused to defend himself with calumnies. Because, according to civil law (Cod. II, iv, De transact. 18), when a man is on trial for his life it is lawful for him to bribe his adversary. Now </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q069" target="st.ii-ii.q069.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q069.contains.st.ii-ii.q069.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q069.contains.st.ii-ii.q069.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q069</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.69 — Sins committed against justice: of the part of the defendant</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q069.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.69 a.3 — Is it lawful to escape condemnation by appealing?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q069.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem unlawful for the accused to escape judgment by appealing. The Apostle says ( Romans 13:1 ): "Let every soul be subject to the higher powers." Now the accused by appealing refuses to be subject to a higher p</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q069" target="st.ii-ii.q069.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q069.contains.st.ii-ii.q069.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q069.contains.st.ii-ii.q069.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q069</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.69 — Sins committed against justice: of the part of the defendant</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q069.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.69 a.4 — Is it lawful for one who has been condemned to defend himself by violence if he be able to do so?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q069.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a man who is condemned to death may lawfully defend himself if he can. For it is always lawful to do that to which nature inclines us, as being of natural right, so to speak. Now, to resist corruption </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q070" target="concept.witness_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q070.treated_in.concept.witness_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q070.treated_in.concept.witness_role</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q070</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.70 — Injustice with regard to the person of the witness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.witness_role</data>
  <data key="d12">Witness</data>
  <data key="d13">role</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q070-treated-in-concept-witness-role-st-ii-ii-q070-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q070.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">We must make a distinction in the matter of giving evidence: because sometimes a certain man's evidence is necessary , and sometimes not. If the necessary evidence is that of a man subject to a superior whom, in matters pertaining to justice , he is bound to o</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q070" target="st.ii-ii.q070.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q070.contains.st.ii-ii.q070.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q070.contains.st.ii-ii.q070.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q070</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.70 — Injustice with regard to the person of the witness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q070.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.70 a.1 — Is a man bound to give evidence?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q070.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a man is not bound to give evidence. Augustine say (QQ. Genesis 1:26 ) [Cf. Contra Faust. xxii, 33,34, that when Abraham said of his wife ( Genesis 20:2 ), "She is my sister," he wished the truth to be</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q070" target="st.ii-ii.q070.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q070.contains.st.ii-ii.q070.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q070.contains.st.ii-ii.q070.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q070</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.70 — Injustice with regard to the person of the witness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q070.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.70 a.2 — Does the evidence of two or three witnesses suffice?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q070.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the evidence of two or three persons is not sufficient. For judgment requires certitude . Now certitude of the truth is not obtained by the assertions of two or three witnesses , for we read that Nabot</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q070" target="st.ii-ii.q070.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q070.contains.st.ii-ii.q070.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q070.contains.st.ii-ii.q070.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q070</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.70 — Injustice with regard to the person of the witness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q070.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.70 a.3 — May a man's evidence be rejected without any fault on his part?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q070.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a man's evidence ought not to be rejected except on account of some fault. For it a penalty on some that their evidence is inadmissible, as in the case of those who are branded with infamy . Now a pena</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q070" target="st.ii-ii.q070.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q070.contains.st.ii-ii.q070.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q070.contains.st.ii-ii.q070.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q070</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.70 — Injustice with regard to the person of the witness</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q070.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.70 a.4 — Is it a mortal sin to bear false witness?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q070.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not always a mortal sin to give false evidence. For a person may happen to give false evidence, through ignorance of fact. Now such ignorance excuses from mortal sin . Therefore the giving of fal</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q071" target="concept.advocate_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q071.treated_in.concept.advocate_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q071.treated_in.concept.advocate_role</data>
