  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">that it would be a sin not to do so: although it would be praiseworthy to do so where one is not bound to. Therefore an advocate is not always bound to defend the suits of the poor , but only when the aforesaid circumstances concur, else he would have to put aside all other business, and</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q071" target="st.ii-ii.q071.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q071.contains.st.ii-ii.q071.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q071.contains.st.ii-ii.q071.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.71 — Injustice in judgment: the part of counsel</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q071.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.71 a.1 — Is an advocate bound to defend the suits of the poor?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q071.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that an advocate is bound to defend the suits of the poor. For it is written ( Exodus 23:5 ): "If thou see the ass of him that hateth thee lie underneath his burden, thou shalt not pass by, but shall lift h</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q071" target="st.ii-ii.q071.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q071.contains.st.ii-ii.q071.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q071.contains.st.ii-ii.q071.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.71 — Injustice in judgment: the part of counsel</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q071.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.71 a.2 — Should certain persons be prohibited from exercising the office of advocate?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q071.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem unfitting for the law to debar certain persons from the office of advocate. For no man should be debarred from doing works of mercy . Now it belongs to the works of mercy to defend a man's suit, as stated a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q071" target="st.ii-ii.q071.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q071.contains.st.ii-ii.q071.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q071.contains.st.ii-ii.q071.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.71 — Injustice in judgment: the part of counsel</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q071.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.71 a.3 — Does an advocate sin by defending an unjust cause?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q071.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that an advocate does not sin by defending an unjust cause . For just as a physician proves his skill by healing a desperate disease, so does an advocate prove his skill, if he can defend an unjust cause . </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q071" target="st.ii-ii.q071.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q071.contains.st.ii-ii.q071.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q071.contains.st.ii-ii.q071.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q071</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.71 — Injustice in judgment: the part of counsel</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q071.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.71 a.4 — Does he sin if he accept a fee for defending a suit?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q071.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem unlawful for an advocate to take a fee for pleading. Works of mercy should not be done with a view to human remuneration, according to Luke 14:12 , "When thou makest a dinner or a supper, call not thy frien</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q072" target="concept.reviling" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q072.treated_in.concept.reviling">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q072.treated_in.concept.reviling</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q072</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.72 — Reviling</data>
