  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.reviling</data>
  <data key="d12">Reviling</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q072-treated-in-concept-reviling-st-ii-ii-q072-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">Reviling denotes the dishonoring of a person , and this happens in two ways: for since honor results from excellence, one person dishonors another, first, by depriving</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q072" target="st.ii-ii.q072.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q072.contains.st.ii-ii.q072.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q072.contains.st.ii-ii.q072.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q072</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.72 — Reviling</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q072.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.72 a.1 — What is reviling?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that reviling does not consist in words. Reviling implies some injury inflicted on one's neighbor, since it is a kind of injustice . But words seem to inflict no injury on one's neighbor, either in his pers</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q072" target="st.ii-ii.q072.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q072.contains.st.ii-ii.q072.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q072.contains.st.ii-ii.q072.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q072</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.72 — Reviling</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q072.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.72 a.2 — Is every reviling a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that reviling or railing is not a mortal sin . For no mortal sin is an act of virtue . Now railing is the act of a virtue , viz. of wittiness eutrapelia [Cf. I-II:60:5 ] to which it pertains to rail well, a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q072" target="st.ii-ii.q072.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q072.contains.st.ii-ii.q072.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q072.contains.st.ii-ii.q072.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q072</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.72 — Reviling</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q072.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.72 a.3 — Should one check revilers?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one ought not to suffer oneself to be reviled. For he that suffers himself to be reviled, encourages the reviler. But one ought not to do this. Therefore one ought not to suffer oneself to be reviled, </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q072" target="st.ii-ii.q072.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q072.contains.st.ii-ii.q072.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q072.contains.st.ii-ii.q072.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q072</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.72 — Reviling</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q072.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.72 a.4 — The origin of reviling</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that reviling does not arise from anger . For it is written ( Proverbs 11:2 ): "Where pride is, there shall also be reviling [ Douay : 'reproach']." But anger is a vice distinct from pride . Therefore revil</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073" target="concept.backbiting" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q073.treated_in.concept.backbiting">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q073.treated_in.concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 — Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d12">Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q073-treated-in-concept-backbiting-st-ii-ii-q073-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">enly, and this is done by reviling him, as stated above ( II-II:72:1 )—and in another way secretly, and this is done by backbiting. Now from the fact that one man openly utters words against another man , he would appear to think little of him, so that for this reason he dishonors him, so</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073" target="st.ii-ii.q073.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q073.contains.st.ii-ii.q073.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q073.contains.st.ii-ii.q073.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 — Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q073.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.73 a.1 — What is backbiting?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that backbiting is not as defined by some [Albert the Great, Sum. Theol. II, cxvii.], "the blackening of another's good name by words uttered in secret." For "secretly" and "openly" are circumstances that d</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073" target="st.ii-ii.q073.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q073.contains.st.ii-ii.q073.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q073.contains.st.ii-ii.q073.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 — Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q073.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.73 a.2 — Is it a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that backbiting is not a mortal sin . For no act of virtue is a mortal sin . Now, to reveal an unknown sin , which pertains to backbiting, as stated above ( Article 1, Reply to Objection 3 ), is an act of t</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073" target="st.ii-ii.q073.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q073.contains.st.ii-ii.q073.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q073.contains.st.ii-ii.q073.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 — Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q073.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.73 a.3 — Its comparison with other sins</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that backbiting is the gravest of all sins committed against one's neighbor. Because a gloss on Psalm 108:4 , "Instead of making me a return of love they detracted me," a gloss says: "Those who detract Chri</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073" target="st.ii-ii.q073.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q073.contains.st.ii-ii.q073.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q073.contains.st.ii-ii.q073.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 — Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q073.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.73 a.4 — Is it a sin to listen to backbiting?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the listener who suffers a backbiter does not sin grievously. For a man is not under greater obligations to others than to himself. But it is praiseworthy for a man to suffer his own backbiters: for Gr</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q074" target="concept.tale_bearing" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q074.treated_in.concept.tale_bearing">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q074.treated_in.concept.tale_bearing</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q074</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.74 — Tale-bearing</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.tale_bearing</data>
  <data key="d12">Tale-Bearing</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q074-treated-in-concept-tale-bearing-st-ii-ii-q074-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q074.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">The tale-bearer and the backbiter agree in matter , and also in form or mode of speaking, since they both speak evil secretly of their neighbor: and for this reason these terms are sometimes used one for the other. Hence a gloss on Sirach 5:16 , "Be not called</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q074" target="st.ii-ii.q074.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q074.contains.st.ii-ii.q074.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q074.contains.st.ii-ii.q074.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q074</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.74 — Tale-bearing</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q074.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.74 a.1 — Is tale-bearing a sin distinct from backbiting?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q074.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that tale-bearing is not a distinct sin from backbiting. Isidore says (Etym. x): "The susurro [tale-bearer] takes his name from the sound of his speech, for he speaks disparagingly not to the face but into </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q074" target="st.ii-ii.q074.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q074.contains.st.ii-ii.q074.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q074.contains.st.ii-ii.q074.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q074</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.74 — Tale-bearing</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q074.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.74 a.2 — Which of the two is the more grievous?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q074.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that backbiting is a graver sin than tale-bearing. For sins of word consist in speaking evil . Now a backbiter speaks of his neighbor things that are evil simply, for such things lead to the loss or depreci</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q075" target="concept.derision" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q075.treated_in.concept.derision">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q075.treated_in.concept.derision</data>
