  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q075-treated-in-concept-derision-st-ii-ii-q075-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q075.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">ider intends to shame the person he derides. And since this end is distinct from the others, it follows that the sin of derision is distinct from the foregoing sins .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q075" target="st.ii-ii.q075.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q075.contains.st.ii-ii.q075.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q075.contains.st.ii-ii.q075.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q075</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.75 — Derision</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q075.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.75 a.1 — Is derision a special sin distinct from the other sins whereby one's neighbor is injured by words?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q075.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that derision is not a special sin distinct from those mentioned above. For laughing to scorn is apparently the same as derision. But laughing to scorn pertains to reviling. Therefore derision would seem no</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q075" target="st.ii-ii.q075.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q075.contains.st.ii-ii.q075.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q075.contains.st.ii-ii.q075.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q075</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.75 — Derision</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q075.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.75 a.2 — Is derision a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q075.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that derision cannot be a mortal sin . Every mortal sin is contrary to charity . But derision does not seem contrary to charity , for sometimes it takes place in jest among friends, wherefore it is known as</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q076" target="concept.cursing" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q076.treated_in.concept.cursing">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q076.treated_in.concept.cursing</data>
