  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q077-treated-in-concept-cheating-st-ii-ii-q077-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q077.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It is altogether sinful to have recourse to deceit in order to sell a thing for more than its just price, because this is to deceive one's neighbor so as to injure him. Hence Tully says (De Offic. iii, 15): "Contracts should be entirely free from double-dealin</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q077" target="st.ii-ii.q077.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q077.contains.st.ii-ii.q077.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q077.contains.st.ii-ii.q077.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q077</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.77 — Cheating, which is committed in buying and selling</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q077.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.77 a.1 — Unjust sales as regards the price: namely, is it lawful to sell a thing for more than its worth?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q077.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is lawful to sell a thing for more than its worth. On the commutations of human life, civil laws determine that which is just. Now according to these laws it is just for buyer and seller to deceive </data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q077" target="st.ii-ii.q077.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q077.contains.st.ii-ii.q077.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q077.contains.st.ii-ii.q077.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q077</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.77 — Cheating, which is committed in buying and selling</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q077.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.77 a.2 — Unjust sales on the part of the thing sold</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q077.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a sale is not rendered unjust and unlawful through a fault in the thing sold. For less account should be taken of the other parts of a thing than of what belongs to its substance . Yet the sale of a th</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q077" target="st.ii-ii.q077.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q077.contains.st.ii-ii.q077.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q077.contains.st.ii-ii.q077.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q077</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.77 — Cheating, which is committed in buying and selling</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q077.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.77 a.3 — Is the seller bound to reveal a fault in the thing sold?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q077.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that the seller is not bound to state the defects of the thing sold. Since the seller does not bind the buyer to buy, he would seem to leave it to him to judge of the goods offered for sale. Now judgment ab</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q077" target="st.ii-ii.q077.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q077.contains.st.ii-ii.q077.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q077.contains.st.ii-ii.q077.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q077</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.77 — Cheating, which is committed in buying and selling</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q077.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.77 a.4 — Is it lawful in trading to sell a thing at a higher price than was paid for it?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q077.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not lawful, in trading, to sell a thing for a higher price than we paid for it. For Chrysostom [Hom. xxxviii in the Opus Imperfectum, falsely ascribed to St. John Chrysostom ] says on Matthew 21:</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q078" target="concept.usury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q078.treated_in.concept.usury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q078.treated_in.concept.usury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q078</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.78 — The sin of usury</data>
