  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q078.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">To take usury for money lent is unjust in itself, because this is to sell what does not exist , and this evidently leads to inequality which is contrary to justice . In orde</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q078" target="st.ii-ii.q078.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q078.contains.st.ii-ii.q078.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q078.contains.st.ii-ii.q078.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q078</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.78 — The sin of usury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q078.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.78 a.1 — Is it a sin to take money as a price for money lent, which is to receive usury?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q078.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not a sin to take usury for money lent. For no man sins through following the example of Christ . But Our Lord said of Himself ( Luke 19:23 ): "At My coming I might have exacted it," i.e. the mon</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q078" target="st.ii-ii.q078.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q078.contains.st.ii-ii.q078.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q078.contains.st.ii-ii.q078.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q078</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.78 — The sin of usury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q078.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.78 a.2 — Is it lawful to lend money for any other kind of consideration, by way of payment for the loan?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q078.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that one may ask for some other kind of consideration for money lent. For everyone may lawfully seek to indemnify himself. Now sometimes a man suffers loss through lending money. Therefore he may lawfully a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q078" target="st.ii-ii.q078.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q078.contains.st.ii-ii.q078.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q078.contains.st.ii-ii.q078.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q078</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.78 — The sin of usury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q078.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.78 a.3 — Is a man bound to restore just gains derived from money taken in usury?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q078.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a man is bound to restore whatever profits he has made out of money gotten by usury. For the Apostle says ( Romans 11:16 ): "If the root be holy , so are the branches." Therefore likewise if the root b</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q078" target="st.ii-ii.q078.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q078.contains.st.ii-ii.q078.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q078.contains.st.ii-ii.q078.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q078</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.78 — The sin of usury</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q078.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.78 a.4 — Is it lawful to borrow money under a condition of usury?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q078.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that it is not lawful to borrow money under a condition of usury. For the Apostle says ( Romans 1:32 ) that they "are worthy of death . . . not only they that do" these sins , "but they also that consent to</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q079" target="concept.omission" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q079.treated_in.concept.omission">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q079.treated_in.concept.omission</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q079</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.79 — The quasi-integral parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.omission</data>
  <data key="d12">Omission</data>
  <data key="d13">sin_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q079-treated-in-concept-omission-st-ii-ii-q079-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q079.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">omission signifies the non-fulfilment of a good , not indeed of any good , but of a good that is due. Now good under the aspect of due belongs properly to justice ; to</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q079" target="st.ii-ii.q079.a001" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q079.contains.st.ii-ii.q079.a001">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q079.contains.st.ii-ii.q079.a001</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q079</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.79 — The quasi-integral parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q079.a001</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.79 a.1 — Are these two parts of justice?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q079.a001.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that to decline from evil and to do good are not parts of justice . For it belongs to every virtue to perform a good deed and to avoid an evil one. But parts do not exceed the whole. Therefore to decline fr</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q079" target="st.ii-ii.q079.a002" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q079.contains.st.ii-ii.q079.a002">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q079.contains.st.ii-ii.q079.a002</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q079</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.79 — The quasi-integral parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q079.a002</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.79 a.2 — Is transgression a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q079.a002.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that transgression is not a special sin . For no species is included in the definition of its genus. Now transgression is included in the definition of sin ; because Ambrose says (De Parad. viii) that sin i</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q079" target="st.ii-ii.q079.a003" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q079.contains.st.ii-ii.q079.a003">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q079.contains.st.ii-ii.q079.a003</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q079</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.79 — The quasi-integral parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q079.a003</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.79 a.3 — Is omission a special sin?</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q079.a003.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that omission is not a special sin . For every sin is either original or actual. Now omission is not original sin , for it is not contracted through origin nor is it actual sin , for it may be altogether wi</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q079" target="st.ii-ii.q079.a004" id="structural.st.ii-ii.q079.contains.st.ii-ii.q079.a004">
  <data key="d6">structural.st.ii-ii.q079.contains.st.ii-ii.q079.a004</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q079</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.79 — The quasi-integral parts of Justice</data>
  <data key="d9">question</data>
  <data key="d10">contains_article</data>
  <data key="d11">st.ii-ii.q079.a004</data>
  <data key="d12">II-II q.79 a.4 — The comparison between omission and transgression</data>
  <data key="d13">article</data>
  <data key="d14"></data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q079.a004.obj1</data>
  <data key="d16">structural_editorial</data>
  <data key="d17">It would seem that a sin of omission is more grievous than a sin of transgression. For "delictum" would seem to signify the same as "derelictum" [ Augustine , QQ. in Levit., qu. xx], and therefore is seemingly the same a</data>
  <data key="d18">structural</data>
</edge>
