<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a001" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a001.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a001.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.1 — What is justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a001-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The aforesaid definition of justice is fitting if understood aright. For since every virtue is a habit that is the principle of a good act, a virtue must needs be defined by means of the good act</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a002" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a002.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a002.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.2 — Is justice always towards another?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a002-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:57:1 ) since justice by its name implies equality, it denotes essentially relation to another, for a thing is equal, not to itself, but to another. And forasmuch as it belongs to j</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a003" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a003.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a003.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.3 — Is it a virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a003-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">A human virtue is one "which renders a human act and man himself good " [Ethic. ii, 6, and this can be applied to justice . For a man's act is made good through attaining the rule of reason , which is the rule whereby human acts are regulated. Hence, since justice regulates human</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
