  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">A human virtue is one "which renders a human act and man himself good " [Ethic</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a004" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a004.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a004.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.4 — Is it in the will as its subject?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a004-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The subject of a virtue is the power whose act that virtue aims at rectifying. Now justice does not aim at directing an act of the cognitive power, for we are not said to be just through knowing something aright. Hence the subject of justice is not t</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
