  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.4 — Is it in the will as its subject?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.will</data>
  <data key="d12">Will</data>
  <data key="d13">faculty</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a004-treated-in-concept-will-st-ii-ii-q058-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">petitive power, justice must needs be in some appetitive power as its subject. Now the appetite is twofold; namely, the will which is in the reason and the sensitive appetite which follows on sensitive apprehension, and is divided into the irascible and the concupiscible , as stated</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a005" target="concept.general_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a005.treated_in.concept.general_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a005.treated_in.concept.general_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.5 — Is it a general virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.general_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">General Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a005-treated-in-concept-general-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">can pertain to justice , in so far as it directs man to the common good . It is in this sense that justice is called a general virtue . And since it belongs to the law to direct to the common good , as stated above ( I-II:90:2 ), it follows that the justice which is in this way styled general</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a005" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a005.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a005.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.5 — Is it a general virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a005-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Justice, as stated above ( Article 2 ) directs man in his relations with other men. Now this may happen in two ways: first as regards his relation with individuals , s</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a006" target="concept.general_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a006.treated_in.concept.general_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a006.treated_in.concept.general_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.6 — As a general virtue, is it essentially the same as every virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.general_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">General Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a006-treated-in-concept-general-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">same. Now it is in the latter sense that, according to what has been said ( Article 5 ), legal justice is said to be a general virtue , in as much, to wit, as it directs the acts of the other virtues to its own end, and this is to move all the other virtues by its command; for just as charity</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a006" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a006.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a006.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.6 — As a general virtue, is it essentially the same as every virtue?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a006-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">are not essentially the same. Now it is in the latter sense that, according to what has been said ( Article 5 ), legal justice is said to be a general virtue , in as much, to wit, as it directs the acts of the other virtues to its own end, and this is to move all the other virtues by i</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a007" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a007.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a007.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.7 — Is there a particular justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a007-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 6 ), legal justice is not essentially the same as every virtue , and besides legal justice which directs man immediately to the common good , there is a need for other virtues to</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a007" target="concept.particular_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a007.treated_in.concept.particular_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a007.treated_in.concept.particular_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.7 — Is there a particular justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.particular_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Particular Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a007-treated-in-concept-particular-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">to direct man in relation to himself, such as temperance and fortitude , so too besides legal justice there is need for particular justice to direct man in his relations to other individuals .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a008" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a008.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a008.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.8 — Does particular justice have a matter of its own?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a008-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">sidered; whereas it is in respect of internal passions that we consider man's rectitude in himself. Consequently, since justice is directed to others, it is not about the entire matter of moral virtue , but only about external actions and things, under a certain special aspect of the ob</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a009" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a009.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a009.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.9 — Is it about passions, or about operations only?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a009-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">The true answer to this question may be gathered from a twofold source. First from the subject of justice , i.e. from the will , whose movements or acts are not passions , as stated above ( I-II:22:3 ; I-II:59:4 ), for it is only the sensitive appetite whose moveme</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a010" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a010.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a010.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a010</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.10 — Is the mean of justice the real mean?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a010-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a010-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a010.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">mself, so that with them the mean is only that which is fixed by reason in our regard. On the other hand, the matter of justice is external operation, in so far as an operation or the thing used in that operation is duly proportionate to another person , wherefore the mean of justice co</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a011" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a011.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a011.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.11 — Is the act of justice to render to everyone his own?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a011-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a011-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above (Articles 8 and 10 ), the matter of justice is an external operation in so far as either it or the thing we use by it is made proportionate to some other person to whom we are related by justice . Now ea</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a011" target="concept.rendering_due" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a011.treated_in.concept.rendering_due">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a011.treated_in.concept.rendering_due</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a011</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.11 — Is the act of justice to render to everyone his own?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.rendering_due</data>
  <data key="d12">Rendering Due</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a011-treated-in-concept-rendering-due-st-ii-ii-q058-a011-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a011.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">at which is due to him according to equality of proportion. Therefore the proper act of justice is nothing else than to render to each one his own.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q058.a012" target="concept.justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a012.treated_in.concept.justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q058.a012.treated_in.concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q058.a012</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.58 a.12 — Is justice the chief of the moral virtues?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q058-a012-treated-in-concept-justice-st-ii-ii-q058-a012-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q058.a012.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">If we speak of legal justice , it is evident that it stands foremost among all the moral virtues , for as much as the common good transcends the individual good of one person . On this sen</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q059.a001" target="concept.injustice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q059.a001.treated_in.concept.injustice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q059.a001.treated_in.concept.injustice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q059.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.59 a.1 — Is injustice a special vice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.injustice</data>
  <data key="d12">Injustice</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q059-a001-treated-in-concept-injustice-st-ii-ii-q059-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q059.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Injustice is twofold. First there is illegal injustice which is opposed to legal justice : and this is essentially a special vice , in so far as it regards a special obj</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q059.a002" target="concept.injustice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q059.a002.treated_in.concept.injustice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q059.a002.treated_in.concept.injustice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q059.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.59 a.2 — Is it proper to the unjust man to do unjust deeds?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.injustice</data>
  <data key="d12">Injustice</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q059-a002-treated-in-concept-injustice-st-ii-ii-q059-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q059.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Even as the object of justice is something equal in external things, so too the object of injustice is something unequal, through more or less being assigned to some person than is due to him. To this object the habit of injustice is compared by means of its</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q059.a003" target="concept.injustice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q059.a003.treated_in.concept.injustice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q059.a003.treated_in.concept.injustice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q059.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.59 a.3 — Can one suffer injustice willingly?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.injustice</data>
  <data key="d12">Injustice</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q059-a003-treated-in-concept-injustice-st-ii-ii-q059-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q059.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">us, he is active rather than passive. Accordingly we must conclude that properly and strictly speaking no man can do an injustice except voluntarily , nor suffer an injustice save involuntarily; but that accidentally and materially so to speak, it is possible for that which is unjust in i</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q059.a004" target="concept.injustice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q059.a004.treated_in.concept.injustice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q059.a004.treated_in.concept.injustice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q059.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.59 a.4 — Is injustice a mortal sin according to its genus?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.injustice</data>
  <data key="d12">Injustice</data>
  <data key="d13">vice</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q059-a004-treated-in-concept-injustice-st-ii-ii-q059-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q059.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">inflicted on another person is of itself contrary to charity , which moves us to will the good of another. And so since injustice always consists in an injury inflicted on another person , it is evident that to do an injustice is a mortal sin according to its genus.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a001" target="concept.judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a001.treated_in.concept.judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a001.treated_in.concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.1 — Is judgment an act of justice?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a001-treated-in-concept-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Judgment properly denotes the act of a judge as such. Now a judge [judex] is so called because he asserts the right [jus dicens] and right is the object of justice , as</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a002" target="concept.judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a002.treated_in.concept.judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a002.treated_in.concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.2 — Is it lawful to judge?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a002-treated-in-concept-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Judgment is lawful in so far as it is an act of justice . Now it follows from what has been stated above ( Article 1, Replies to 1 and 3 ) that three conditions are req</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a003" target="concept.judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a003.treated_in.concept.judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a003.treated_in.concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.3 — Should judgment be based on suspicions?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a003-treated-in-concept-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ame gloss goes on to say: "If then we cannot avoid suspicions, because we are human , we must nevertheless restrain our judgment, and refrain from forming a definite and fixed opinion." The third degree is when a judge goes so far as to condemn a man on suspicion: this pertains directly</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a003" target="concept.rash_judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a003.treated_in.concept.rash_judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a003.treated_in.concept.rash_judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.3 — Should judgment be based on suspicions?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.rash_judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Rash Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a003-treated-in-concept-rash-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As Tully says (De Invent. Rhet. ii), suspicion denotes evil thinking based on slight indications, and this is due to three causes . First, from a man being evil in himself, and from this very fact, as though conscious of his own wickedness , he is prone to thi</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a004" target="concept.judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a004.treated_in.concept.judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a004.treated_in.concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.4 — Should doubts be interpreted favorably?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a004-treated-in-concept-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 3, Reply to Objection 2 ), things from the very fact that a man thinks ill of another without sufficient cause , he injures and despises him. Now no man ought to despise or in any way injure another man without urgent cause : and, con</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a005" target="concept.judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a005.treated_in.concept.judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a005.treated_in.concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.5 — Should judgment always be given according to the written law?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a005-treated-in-concept-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1 ), judgment is nothing else but a decision or determination of what is just. Now a thing becomes just in two ways: first by the very nature of the case, and this is called</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a005" target="concept.law" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a005.treated_in.concept.law">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a005.treated_in.concept.law</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.5 — Should judgment always be given according to the written law?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.law</data>
  <data key="d12">Law</data>
  <data key="d13">law</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a005-treated-in-concept-law-st-ii-ii-q060-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ight," secondly by some agreement between men, and this is called "positive right," as stated above ( II-II:57:2 ). Now laws are written for the purpose of manifesting both these rights, but in different ways. For the written law does indeed contain natural right, but it does not es</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a006" target="concept.judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a006.treated_in.concept.judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a006.treated_in.concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.6 — Is judgment perverted by being usurped?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a006-treated-in-concept-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Since judgment should be pronounced according to the written law , as stated above ( Article 5 ), he that pronounces judgment, interprets, in a way, the letter of the law , b</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q060.a006" target="concept.usurped_judgment" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a006.treated_in.concept.usurped_judgment">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q060.a006.treated_in.concept.usurped_judgment</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q060.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.60 a.6 — Is judgment perverted by being usurped?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.usurped_judgment</data>
  <data key="d12">Usurped Judgment</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q060-a006-treated-in-concept-usurped-judgment-st-ii-ii-q060-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q060.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Since judgment should be pronounced according to the written law , as stated above ( Article 5 ), he that pronounces judgment, interprets, in a way, the letter of the law , by applying it to some particular case. Now since it belongs to the same authority to i</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061.a001" target="concept.commutative_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a001.treated_in.concept.commutative_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a001.treated_in.concept.commutative_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 a.1 — Are there two species of justice, viz. distributive and commutative?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.commutative_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Commutative Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q061-a001-treated-in-concept-commutative-justice-st-ii-ii-q061-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">of one part to another, to which corresponds the order of one private individual to another. This order is directed by commutative justice , which is concerned about the mutual dealings between two persons . On the second place there is the order of the whole towards the parts, to which correspond</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061.a001" target="concept.distributive_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a001.treated_in.concept.distributive_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a001.treated_in.concept.distributive_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 a.1 — Are there two species of justice, viz. distributive and commutative?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.distributive_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Distributive Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q061-a001-treated-in-concept-distributive-justice-st-ii-ii-q061-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">responds the order of that which belongs to the community in relation to each single person . This order is directed by distributive justice , which distributes common goods proportionately. Hence there are two species of justice , distributive and commutative.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061.a002" target="concept.fairness_in_distribution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a002.treated_in.concept.fairness_in_distribution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a002.treated_in.concept.fairness_in_distribution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 a.2 — In either case, is the mean taken in the same way?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.fairness_in_distribution</data>
  <data key="d12">Fairness in Distribution</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q061-a002-treated-in-concept-fairness-in-distribution-st-ii-ii-q061-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1 ), in distributive justice something is given to a private individual , in so far as what belongs to the whole is due to the part, and in a quantity that is proportionate to the importance of the position of that part in respect of</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061.a002" target="concept.fairness_in_exchange" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a002.treated_in.concept.fairness_in_exchange">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a002.treated_in.concept.fairness_in_exchange</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 a.2 — In either case, is the mean taken in the same way?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.fairness_in_exchange</data>
  <data key="d12">Fairness in Exchange</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q061-a002-treated-in-concept-fairness-in-exchange-st-ii-ii-q061-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1 ), in distributive justice something is given to a private individual , in so far as what belongs to the whole is due to the part, and in a quantity that is proportionate to the importance of the position of that part in respect of</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061.a003" target="concept.particular_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a003.treated_in.concept.particular_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a003.treated_in.concept.particular_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 a.3 — Is their matter uniform or manifold?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.particular_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Particular Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q061-a003-treated-in-concept-particular-justice-st-ii-ii-q061-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:51:10 ), justice is about certain external operations, namely distribution and commutation. These consist in the use of certain externals, whether things, persons or even works: of things, as when one man takes from or restores to anoth</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q061.a004" target="concept.particular_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a004.treated_in.concept.particular_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q061.a004.treated_in.concept.particular_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q061.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.61 a.4 — In any of these species, is the just the same as counter-passion?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.particular_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Particular Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q061-a004-treated-in-concept-particular-justice-st-ii-ii-q061-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q061.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Retaliation [contrapassum] denotes equal passion repaid for previous action; and the expression applies most properly to injurious passions and actions, whereby a man harms the person of his neighbor; for instance if a man strike, that he be struck back. This</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a001" target="concept.commutative_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a001.treated_in.concept.commutative_justice">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a001.treated_in.concept.commutative_justice</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.1 — Of what is it an act?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.commutative_justice</data>
  <data key="d12">Commutative Justice</data>
  <data key="d13">virtue</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a001-treated-in-concept-commutative-justice-st-ii-ii-q062-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">in restitution we consider the equality of justice attending the payment of one thing for another, and this belongs to commutative justice . Hence restitution is an act of commutative justice , occasioned by one person having what belongs to another, either with his consent, for instance on loan o</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a001" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a001.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a001.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.1 — Of what is it an act?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a001-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">To restore is seemingly the same as to reinstate a person in the possession or dominion of his thing, so that in restitution we consider the equality of justice attending the payment of one thing for another, and this belongs to commutative justice . Hence restitution is an act of co</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a002" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a002.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a002.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.2 — Is it always of necessity for salvation to restore what one has taken away?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a002-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Restitution as stated above ( Article 1 ) is an act of commutative justice , and this demands a certain equality. Wherefore restitution denotes the return of the thing unj</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a003" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a003.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a003.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.3 — Is it necessary to restore more than has been taken away?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a003-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">of the thing, as when a person intends to use violence but fails. As regards the first, the remedy is applied by making restitution, since thereby equality is re-established; and for this it is enough that a man restore just so much as he has belonging to another. But as regards the sin , t</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a004" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a004.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a004.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.4 — Is it necessary to restore what one has not taken away?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a004-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">n your own is called 'gain,' and to have less than you started with is called 'loss.'] Therefore a man is bound to make restitution according to the loss he has brought upon another. Now a man suffers a loss in two ways. First, by being deprived of what he actually has; and a loss of this k</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a005" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a005.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a005.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.5 — Is it necessary to make restitution to the person from whom something has been taken?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a005-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Restitution re-establishes the equality of commutative justice , which equality consists in the equalizing of thing to thing, as stated above ( Article 2 ; II-II:58:10 ).</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a006" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a006.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a006.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.6 — Is the person who has taken something away bound to restore it?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a006-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">times it is injurious, i.e. against the will of the owner, as in theft and robbery: in which case the thief is bound to restitution not only by reason of the thing, but also by reason of the injurious action, even though the thing is no longer in his possession. For just as a man who strike</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a007" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a007.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a007.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.7 — Is any other person bound to restitution?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a007-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 6 ), a person is bound to restitution not only on account of someone else's property which he has taken, but also on account of the injurious taking. Hence whoever is cause of an unjust taking is b</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q062.a008" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a008.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q062.a008.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q062.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.62 a.8 — Is one bound to restore at once?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q062-a008-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q062-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q062.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">once, according to Sirach 21:2 , "Flee from sin as from the face of a serpent." Consequently one is bound to immediate restitution, if possible, or to ask for a respite from the person who is empowered to grant the use of the thing.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q063.a001" target="concept.distributive_justice" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q063.a001.treated_in.concept.distributive_justice">
