  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q064-a003-treated-in-concept-private-execution-st-ii-ii-q064-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q064.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 2 ), it is lawful to kill an evildoer in so far as it is directed to the welfare of the whole community, so that it belongs to him alone who has charge of the community's welfare. Thus it belongs to a physician to cut off a decayed li</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q064.a004" target="concept.life" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a004.treated_in.concept.life">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a004.treated_in.concept.life</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q064.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.64 a.4 — Is this lawful to a cleric?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.life</data>
  <data key="d12">Life</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q064-a004-treated-in-concept-life-st-ii-ii-q064-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q064.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">It is unlawful for clerics to kill, for two reasons. First, because they are chosen for the ministry of the altar, whereon is represented the Passion of Christ slain "Who, when He was struck did not strike [ Vulgate : 'When He suffered, He threatened not']" (</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q064.a005" target="concept.life" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a005.treated_in.concept.life">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a005.treated_in.concept.life</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q064.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.64 a.5 — Is it lawful to kill oneself?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.life</data>
  <data key="d12">Life</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q064-a005-treated-in-concept-life-st-ii-ii-q064-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q064.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">munity. Hence by killing himself he injures the community, as the Philosopher declares (Ethic. v, 11). Thirdly, because life is God's gift to man , and is subject to His power, Who kills and makes to live. Hence whoever takes his own life, sins against God , even as he who kills anot</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q064.a005" target="concept.suicide" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a005.treated_in.concept.suicide">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a005.treated_in.concept.suicide</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q064.a005</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.64 a.5 — Is it lawful to kill oneself?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.suicide</data>
  <data key="d12">Suicide</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q064-a005-treated-in-concept-suicide-st-ii-ii-q064-a005-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q064.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">, the result being that everything naturally keeps itself in being, and resists corruptions so far as it can. Wherefore suicide is contrary to the inclination of nature , and to charity whereby every man should love himself. Hence suicide is always a mortal sin , as being contrary to th</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q064.a006" target="concept.life" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a006.treated_in.concept.life">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a006.treated_in.concept.life</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q064.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.64 a.6 — Is it lawful to kill a just man?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.life</data>
  <data key="d12">Life</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q064-a006-treated-in-concept-life-st-ii-ii-q064-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q064.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e slaying of a sinner becomes lawful in relation to the common good , which is corrupted by sin . On the other hand the life of righteous men preserves and forwards the common good , since they are the chief part of the community. Therefore it is in no way lawful to slay the innocent</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q064.a006" target="concept.unjust_killing" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a006.treated_in.concept.unjust_killing">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a006.treated_in.concept.unjust_killing</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q064.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.64 a.6 — Is it lawful to kill a just man?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.unjust_killing</data>
  <data key="d12">Unjust Killing</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q064-a006-treated-in-concept-unjust-killing-st-ii-ii-q064-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q064.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">An individual man may be considered in two ways: first, in himself; secondly, in relation to something else. If we consider a man in himself, it is unlawful to kill any man , since in every man though he be sinful , we ought to love the nature which God has ma</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q064.a007" target="concept.life" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a007.treated_in.concept.life">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a007.treated_in.concept.life</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q064.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.64 a.7 — Is it lawful to kill a man in self-defense?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.life</data>
  <data key="d12">Life</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q064-a007-treated-in-concept-life-st-ii-ii-q064-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q064.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">above ( II-II:43:3 ; I-II:12:1 ). Accordingly the act of self-defense may have two effects, one is the saving of one's life, the other is the slaying of the aggressor. Therefore this act, since one's intention is to save one's own life, is not unlawful, seeing that it is natural to</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q064.a008" target="concept.life" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a008.treated_in.concept.life">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q064.a008.treated_in.concept.life</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q064.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.64 a.8 — Is accidental homicide a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.life</data>
  <data key="d12">Life</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q064-a008-treated-in-concept-life-st-ii-ii-q064-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q064.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">, according to jurists, if a man pursue a lawful occupation and take due care, the result being that a person loses his life, he is not guilty of that person's death: whereas if he be occupied with something unlawful, or even with something lawful, but without due care, he does not e</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q065.a001" target="concept.bodily_integrity" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q065.a001.treated_in.concept.bodily_integrity">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q065.a001.treated_in.concept.bodily_integrity</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q065.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.65 a.1 — The mutilation of members</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.bodily_integrity</data>
  <data key="d12">Bodily Integrity</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q065-a001-treated-in-concept-bodily-integrity-st-ii-ii-q065-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q065.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Since a member is part of the whole human body, it is for the sake of the whole, as the imperfect for the perfect. Hence a member of the human body is to be disposed of according as it is expedient for the body. Now a member of the human body is of itself usef</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q065.a001" target="concept.maiming" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q065.a001.treated_in.concept.maiming">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q065.a001.treated_in.concept.maiming</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q065.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.65 a.1 — The mutilation of members</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.maiming</data>
  <data key="d12">Maiming</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q065-a001-treated-in-concept-maiming-st-ii-ii-q065-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q065.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Since a member is part of the whole human body, it is for the sake of the whole, as the imperfect for the perfect. Hence a member of the human body is to be disposed of according as it is expedient for the body. Now a member of the human body is of itself usef</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
