  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a005.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">what belongs to another. Secondly, because of the guile or fraud committed by the thief , by laying hands on another's property secretly and cunningly. Wherefore it is evident that every theft is a sin .</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066.a006" target="concept.property" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a006.treated_in.concept.property">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a006.treated_in.concept.property</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066.a006</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 a.6 — Is theft a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.property</data>
  <data key="d12">Property</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q066-a006-treated-in-concept-property-st-ii-ii-q066-a006-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a006.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above, ( II-II:59:4 and Prima Secundae Partis, Question 72, Article 5 ), a mortal sin is one that is contrary to charity as the spiritual life of the soul . Now charity consists principally in the love of God , and secondarily in the love of our neig</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066.a007" target="concept.property" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a007.treated_in.concept.property">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a007.treated_in.concept.property</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 a.7 — Is it lawful to thieve in a case of necessity?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.property</data>
  <data key="d12">Property</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q066-a007-treated-in-concept-property-st-ii-ii-q066-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">anger, and there is no other possible remedy), then it is lawful for a man to succor his own need by means of another's property, by taking it either openly or secretly: nor is this properly speaking theft or robbery.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066.a007" target="concept.theft" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a007.treated_in.concept.theft">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a007.treated_in.concept.theft</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066.a007</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 a.7 — Is it lawful to thieve in a case of necessity?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.theft</data>
  <data key="d12">Theft</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q066-a007-treated-in-concept-theft-st-ii-ii-q066-a007-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a007.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ccor his own need by means of another's property, by taking it either openly or secretly: nor is this properly speaking theft or robbery.</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066.a008" target="concept.property" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a008.treated_in.concept.property">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a008.treated_in.concept.property</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 a.8 — Is every robbery a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.property</data>
  <data key="d12">Property</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
