  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">except through public authority: and, consequently, if a private individual not having public authority takes another's property by violence , he acts unlawfully and commits a robbery, as burglars do. As regards princes, the public power is entrusted to them that they may be the guardian</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066.a008" target="concept.robbery" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a008.treated_in.concept.robbery">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a008.treated_in.concept.robbery</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066.a008</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 a.8 — Is every robbery a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.robbery</data>
  <data key="d12">Robbery</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q066-a008-treated-in-concept-robbery-st-ii-ii-q066-a008-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a008.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Robbery implies a certain violence and coercion employed in taking unjustly from a man that which is his. Now in human society no man can exercise coercion except thro</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q066.a009" target="concept.property" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a009.treated_in.concept.property">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q066.a009.treated_in.concept.property</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q066.a009</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.66 a.9 — Is robbery a more grievous sin than theft?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.property</data>
  <data key="d12">Property</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q066-a009-treated-in-concept-property-st-ii-ii-q066-a009-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q066.a009.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Robbery and theft are sinful , as stated above (Articles 4 and 6 ), on account of the involuntariness on the part of the person from whom something is taken: yet so that in theft the involuntariness is due to ignorance , whereas in robbery it is due to violenc</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067.a001" target="concept.judge_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a001.treated_in.concept.judge_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a001.treated_in.concept.judge_role</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 a.1 — Can a man justly judge one who is not his subject?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judge_role</data>
  <data key="d12">Judge</data>
  <data key="d13">role</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q067-a001-treated-in-concept-judge-role-st-ii-ii-q067-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">A judge's sentence is like a particular law regarding some particular fact. Wherefore just as a general law should have coercive power, as the Philosopher states (Ethi</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067.a001" target="concept.judicial_process" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a001.treated_in.concept.judicial_process">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a001.treated_in.concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 a.1 — Can a man justly judge one who is not his subject?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d12">Judicial Process</data>
  <data key="d13">process</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q067-a001-treated-in-concept-judicial-process-st-ii-ii-q067-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">A judge's sentence is like a particular law regarding some particular fact. Wherefore just as a general law should have coercive power, as the Philosopher states (Ethic. x, 9), so too the sentence of a judge should have coercive power, whereby either party is</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067.a002" target="concept.judicial_process" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a002.treated_in.concept.judicial_process">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a002.treated_in.concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 a.2 — Is it lawful for a judge, on account of the evidence, to deliver judgment in opposition to the truth which is known to him?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d12">Judicial Process</data>
  <data key="d13">process</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q067-a002-treated-in-concept-judicial-process-st-ii-ii-q067-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1 ; II-II:60:6 ) it is the duty of a judge to pronounce judgment in as much as he exercises public authority, wherefore his judgment should be based on information acquired by him, not from his knowledge as a private individual , but</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067.a003" target="concept.accuser_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a003.treated_in.concept.accuser_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a003.treated_in.concept.accuser_role</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 a.3 — Can a judge justly sentence a man who is not accused?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.accuser_role</data>
  <data key="d12">Accuser</data>
  <data key="d13">role</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q067-a003-treated-in-concept-accuser-role-st-ii-ii-q067-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">utor, and the other the defendant. Therefore in criminal cases the judge cannot sentence a man unless the latter has an accuser, according to Acts 25:16 : "It is not the custom of the Romans to condemn any man , before that he who is accused have his accusers present, and have liberty t</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067.a003" target="concept.judicial_process" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a003.treated_in.concept.judicial_process">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a003.treated_in.concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 a.3 — Can a judge justly sentence a man who is not accused?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d12">Judicial Process</data>
  <data key="d13">process</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q067-a003-treated-in-concept-judicial-process-st-ii-ii-q067-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">A judge is an interpreter of justice . Wherefore, as the Philosopher says (Ethic. v, 4), "men have recourse to a judge as to one who is the personification of justice ." Now, as stated above ( II-II:58:2 ), justice is not between a man and himself but between</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q067.a004" target="concept.judicial_process" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a004.treated_in.concept.judicial_process">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q067.a004.treated_in.concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q067.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.67 a.4 — Can he justly remit the punishment?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d12">Judicial Process</data>
  <data key="d13">process</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q067-a004-treated-in-concept-judicial-process-st-ii-ii-q067-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q067.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As may be gathered from what has been said ( A2,3 ), with regard to the question in point, two things may be observed in connection with a judge. One is that he has to judge between accuser and defendant, while the other is that he pronounces the judicial sent</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q068.a001" target="concept.accuser_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q068.a001.treated_in.concept.accuser_role">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q068.a001.treated_in.concept.accuser_role</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q068.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.68 a.1 — Is a man bound to accuse?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.accuser_role</data>
  <data key="d12">Accuser</data>
  <data key="d13">role</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q068-a001-treated-in-concept-accuser-role-st-ii-ii-q068-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q068.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">the injury of the commonwealth, a man is bound to accusation, provided he can offer sufficient proof , since it is the accuser's duty to prove : as, for example, when anyone's sin conduces to the bodily or spiritual corruption of the community. If, however, the sin be not such as to af</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q068.a001" target="concept.judicial_process" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q068.a001.treated_in.concept.judicial_process">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q068.a001.treated_in.concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q068.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.68 a.1 — Is a man bound to accuse?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.judicial_process</data>
  <data key="d12">Judicial Process</data>
  <data key="d13">process</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q068-a001-treated-in-concept-judicial-process-st-ii-ii-q068-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q068.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:33:7 ; II-II:67:3 ad 2 ), the difference between denunciation and accusation is that in denunciation we aim at a brother's amendment, whereas in accusation we intend the punishment of his crime. Now the punishments of this life are soug</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q068.a002" target="concept.accuser_role" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q068.a002.treated_in.concept.accuser_role">
