  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">Reviling denotes the dishonoring of a person , and this happens in two ways: for since honor results from excellence, one person dishonors another, first, by depriving</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q072.a002" target="concept.reviling" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q072.a002.treated_in.concept.reviling">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q072.a002.treated_in.concept.reviling</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q072.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.72 a.2 — Is every reviling a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.reviling</data>
  <data key="d12">Reviling</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q072-a002-treated-in-concept-reviling-st-ii-ii-q072-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e, in sins of word, it seems that we ought to consider with what intention the words are uttered. Since then railing or reviling essentially denotes a dishonoring, if the intention of the utterer is to dishonor the other man , this is properly and essentially to give utterance to railing</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q072.a003" target="concept.reviling" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q072.a003.treated_in.concept.reviling">
