  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.reviling</data>
  <data key="d12">Reviling</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q072-a003-treated-in-concept-reviling-st-ii-ii-q072-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">so, for when He received a blow, He said: "Why strikest thou Me?" ( John 18:23 ). Consequently the same applies to the reviling words that are said against us. For we are bound to hold our minds prepared to submit to be reviled, if it should be expedient. Nevertheless it sometimes behoo</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q072.a004" target="concept.reviling" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q072.a004.treated_in.concept.reviling">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q072.a004.treated_in.concept.reviling</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q072.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.72 a.4 — The origin of reviling</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.reviling</data>
  <data key="d12">Reviling</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q072-a004-treated-in-concept-reviling-st-ii-ii-q072-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q072.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">e chiefly in that one from which it is wont to arise most frequently, through being closely connected with its end. Now reviling is closely connected with anger's end, which is revenge: since the easiest way for the angry man to take revenge on another is to revile him. Therefore revilin</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073.a001" target="concept.backbiting" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a001.treated_in.concept.backbiting">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a001.treated_in.concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 a.1 — What is backbiting?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d12">Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q073-a001-treated-in-concept-backbiting-st-ii-ii-q073-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">enly, and this is done by reviling him, as stated above ( II-II:72:1 )—and in another way secretly, and this is done by backbiting. Now from the fact that one man openly utters words against another man , he would appear to think little of him, so that for this reason he dishonors him, so</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073.a001" target="concept.reputation" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a001.treated_in.concept.reputation">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a001.treated_in.concept.reputation</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 a.1 — What is backbiting?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.reputation</data>
  <data key="d12">Reputation</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q073-a001-treated-in-concept-reputation-st-ii-ii-q073-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">s against another secretly, seems to respect rather than slight him, so that he injures directly, not his honor but his good name , in so far as by uttering such words secretly, he, for his own part, causes his hearers to have a bad opinion of the person against whom he speaks. For the ba</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073.a002" target="concept.backbiting" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a002.treated_in.concept.backbiting">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a002.treated_in.concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 a.2 — Is it a mortal sin?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d12">Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q073-a002-treated-in-concept-backbiting-st-ii-ii-q073-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( II-II:72:2 ), sins of word should be judged chiefly from the intention of the speaker. Now backbiting by its very nature aims at blackening a man's good name . Wherefore, properly speaking, to backbite is to speak ill of an absent person in order to blacken his</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073.a003" target="concept.backbiting" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a003.treated_in.concept.backbiting">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a003.treated_in.concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 a.3 — Its comparison with other sins</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d12">Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q073-a003-treated-in-concept-backbiting-st-ii-ii-q073-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">in to spiritual goods, wherefore it is written ( Proverbs 22:1 ): "A good name is better than great riches ." Therefore backbiting according to its genus is a more grievous sin than theft , but is less grievous than murder or adultery . Nevertheless the order may differ by reason of aggrav</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q073.a004" target="concept.backbiting" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a004.treated_in.concept.backbiting">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q073.a004.treated_in.concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q073.a004</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.73 a.4 — Is it a sin to listen to backbiting?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.backbiting</data>
  <data key="d12">Backbiting</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q073-a004-treated-in-concept-backbiting-st-ii-ii-q073-a004-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q073.a004.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">ecause the sin is pleasing to him, but on account of some human fear. Accordingly we must say that if a man list ens to backbiting without resisting it, he seems to consent to the backbiter, so that he becomes a participator in his sin . And if he induces him to backbite, or at least if th</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
