  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q078.a001.treated_in.concept.usury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q078.a001</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.78 a.1 — Is it a sin to take money as a price for money lent, which is to receive usury?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.usury</data>
  <data key="d12">Usury</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q078-a001-treated-in-concept-usury-st-ii-ii-q078-a001-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q078.a001.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">To take usury for money lent is unjust in itself, because this is to sell what does not exist , and this evidently leads to inequality which is contrary to justice . In orde</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q078.a002" target="concept.usury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q078.a002.treated_in.concept.usury">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q078.a002.treated_in.concept.usury</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q078.a002</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.78 a.2 — Is it lawful to lend money for any other kind of consideration, by way of payment for the loan?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.usury</data>
  <data key="d12">Usury</data>
  <data key="d13">wrong_act</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q078-a002-treated-in-concept-usury-st-ii-ii-q078-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q078.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">According to the Philosopher (Ethic. iv, 1), a thing is reckoned as money "if its value can be measured by money." Consequently, just as it is a sin against justice , to take money, by tacit or express agreement, in return for lending money or anything else th</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q078.a003" target="concept.restitution" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q078.a003.treated_in.concept.restitution">
  <data key="d6">edge.st.ii-ii.q078.a003.treated_in.concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d7">st.ii-ii.q078.a003</data>
  <data key="d8">II-II q.78 a.3 — Is a man bound to restore just gains derived from money taken in usury?</data>
  <data key="d9">article</data>
  <data key="d10">treated_in</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.restitution</data>
  <data key="d12">Restitution</data>
  <data key="d13">act_type</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.st-ii-ii-q078-a003-treated-in-concept-restitution-st-ii-ii-q078-a003-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q078.a003.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">As stated above ( Article 1 ), there are certain things whose use is their consumption, and which do not admit of usufruct, according to law ( Article 1, Response to Objection 3 ). Wherefore if such like things be extorted by means of usury, for instance money</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_structural_editorial</data>
</edge>
<edge source="st.ii-ii.q078.a003" target="concept.usury" id="edge.st.ii-ii.q078.a003.treated_in.concept.usury">
